{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782957415,"nonce":"1cY6zuBrHTYyt/VuI3SWctjWWo8=","kind":"spec","title":"Custom tiers — design spec (draft for review)"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782957415,"nonce":"/u5h3wWZ2gXEM6owVuB9I0LxdIg=","body":"# Custom tiers — design spec (draft for review)\n\nDecisions taken with Trevor 2026-07-02: config files are **YAML only**;\nfavorites/aliases **travel with the tier** (entry DAG, team-shared); this spec\ngets reviewed before any implementation.\n\n## Goal\n\nAny number of user-defined tiers, each typed `personal` or `shared`, each with\nits own remote. The three built-ins stay; `private` remains singular,\nunpushable, and non-replicable (no custom tier may be typed `private` — the\n\"structurally cannot leave\" guarantee stays unique and auditable).\n\n## Model\n\n- A tier is `{name, type: personal|shared}`. Name rules: `[a-z][a-z0-9-]{1,31}`,\n  reserved: `private`, `personal`, `shared`, `pushed`, `incoming`.\n- Ref namespace: `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` (unchanged scheme; names cannot collide\n  with the built-ins by the reserved list).\n- **Definition lives in git config** (machine-local, like remotes today):\n  `kref.tier.\u003cname\u003e = personal|shared`. The remote stays\n  `kref.remote.\u003cname\u003e = \u003cremote\u003e`. Rationale: remotes are already per-machine;\n  a tier definition without its remote is inert, so they belong together.\n- **Discovery over declaration for reads**: list/show/sync-pull resolve tiers\n  from config ∪ existing `refs/kref-*` namespaces, so entries pulled from a\n  teammate who has extra tiers still render (typed as `shared` for display,\n  flagged `(undeclared)`) instead of being invisible. Writes (`new --tier`,\n  `retier`) require the tier to be declared.\n\n## Semantics by surface\n\n- `kref tier add \u003cname\u003e --type personal|shared` / `kref tier rm \u003cname\u003e`\n  (rm refuses while `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` is non-empty; `--force` to orphan) /\n  `kref tier list`.\n- **Ordering/display**: private first, then personal-typed (built-in first,\n  then customs alphabetically), then shared-typed. Glyphs stay type-based\n  (`●` private, `◐` personal-typed, `○` shared-typed); the TIER column shows\n  the name, so customs are distinguishable by name, colored by type.\n- **retier/promote**: promote = \"to the shared-TYPED tier configured as the\n  promotion target\" — with multiple shared tiers, `kref promote` errors unless\n  exactly one shared-typed tier exists or `kref.promote.target` is set.\n  `retier \u003cid\u003e \u003cname\u003e` works for any declared tier; secret rescan fires when\n  the destination type is shared (same fail-closed path as today).\n- **sync**: push/pull iterate all declared tiers with remotes; per-tier\n  pushed-state bookkeeping keys by tier name (`refs/kref-pushed/\u003cname\u003e/...`)\n  — already name-scoped today.\n- **bundle/vault**: `--tier` accepts custom names; vault stays private-only.\n- **completion**: tier enums become dynamic (store-backed), like `--kind`.\n\n## Migration/compat\n\nNone needed pre-release. Ref scheme unchanged for built-ins.\n\n## Open questions for review\n\n1. Display color for custom tiers: inherit the type color (proposal) or a\n   per-tier configurable color in config.yaml?\n2. Should `kref tier add` also set the remote in one step\n   (`--remote \u003cname\u003e [url]`)? (Proposal: yes, optional flags.)\n3. Does `promote`'s multi-shared ambiguity warrant `kref.promote.target` in\n   git config or in the future project config.yaml? (Proposal: git config now,\n   config.yaml may alias it later.)\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- No per-tier encryption, ACLs, or server-side enforcement (unchanged trust\n  model: a remote you can push to is a remote anyone with access can read).\n- Favorites/aliases are a separate spec (synced via entry DAG per decision)."},{"type":9,"timestamp":1782957415,"nonce":"Ux+t0Ai4IPBQaKU2jRzxspuJqrY=","label":"area:design"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1782957415,"nonce":"9ow7opAQxreGbC8zdTgE1Cyj4YU=","actor":"claude","actor_kind":"agent","source_path":"","trigger":"create"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783000156,"nonce":"NbjbSavKVdprzvPSrgjNuJCterU=","body":"# Custom tiers — design spec (approved 2026-07-02)\n\nDecisions taken with Trevor 2026-07-02: config files are **YAML only**;\nfavorites/aliases **travel with the tier** (entry DAG, team-shared). Review\nanswers folded in 2026-07-02 (see \"Resolved questions\"); the spec is now\napproved for implementation.\n\n## Goal\n\nAny number of user-defined tiers, each typed `personal` or `shared`, each with\nits own remote. The three built-ins stay; `private` remains singular,\nunpushable, and non-replicable (no custom tier may be typed `private` — the\n\"structurally cannot leave\" guarantee stays unique and auditable).\n\n## Model\n\n- A tier is `{name, type: personal|shared}`. Name rules: `[a-z][a-z0-9-]{1,31}`,\n  reserved: `private`, `personal`, `shared`, `pushed`, `incoming`.\n- Ref namespace: `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` (unchanged scheme; names cannot collide\n  with the built-ins by the reserved list).\n- **Definition lives in git config** (machine-local, like remotes today):\n  `kref.tier.\u003cname\u003e = personal|shared`. The remote stays\n  `kref.remote.\u003cname\u003e = \u003cremote\u003e`. Rationale: remotes are already per-machine;\n  a tier definition without its remote is inert, so they belong together.\n- **Discovery over declaration for reads**: list/show/sync-pull resolve tiers\n  from config ∪ existing `refs/kref-*` namespaces, so entries pulled from a\n  teammate who has extra tiers still render (typed as `shared` for display,\n  flagged `(undeclared)`) instead of being invisible. Writes (`new --tier`,\n  `retier`) require the tier to be declared.\n\n## Semantics by surface\n\n- `kref tier add \u003cname\u003e --type personal|shared [--remote \u003cname\u003e [url]]` —\n  declaring and wiring the remote in one step (remote flags optional).\n  `kref tier rm \u003cname\u003e` (refuses while `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` is non-empty;\n  `--force` to orphan) / `kref tier list`.\n- **Ordering/display**: private first, then personal-typed (built-in first,\n  then customs alphabetically), then shared-typed. Glyphs AND colors are\n  type-based: `●` red for private, `◐` yellow for personal-typed, `○` green\n  for shared-typed — matching today's palette. The TIER column shows the\n  name, so customs are distinguishable by name, colored by type. No per-tier\n  color configuration.\n- **One movement verb**: `kref promote` and `kref private` are REMOVED\n  (pre-release, no compat shim). `kref retier \u003cid\u003e \u003cname\u003e` is the single way\n  to move an entry; it works for any declared tier, and the secret rescan\n  fires when the destination type is shared (same fail-closed path as today).\n  This also dissolves the \"which shared tier does promote target?\" ambiguity —\n  the user always names the destination.\n- **sync**: push/pull iterate all declared tiers with remotes; per-tier\n  pushed-state bookkeeping keys by tier name (`refs/kref-pushed/\u003cname\u003e/...`)\n  — already name-scoped today.\n- **bundle/vault**: `--tier` accepts custom names; vault stays private-only.\n- **completion**: tier enums become dynamic (store-backed), like `--kind`.\n\n## Migration/compat\n\nNone needed pre-release. Ref scheme unchanged for built-ins. Removing\n`promote`/`private` touches: commands, completion, help preamble, README,\ndemo tapes (if they use promote), and the retier quarantine hint text\n(`kref retier \u003cid\u003e shared` already the canonical phrasing).\n\n## Resolved questions (Trevor, 2026-07-02)\n\n1. Display color for custom tiers → **inherit the type color** (private=red,\n   personal=yellow, shared=green). No per-tier color config.\n2. `kref tier add --remote` in one step → **yes** (optional flags).\n3. `promote` multi-shared-tier targeting → **moot**: `promote` and `private`\n   are removed entirely; `retier` is sufficient and always explicit.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- No per-tier encryption, ACLs, or server-side enforcement (unchanged trust\n  model: a remote you can push to is a remote anyone with access can read).\n- Favorites/aliases are a separate spec (synced via entry DAG per decision).\n"},{"type":4,"timestamp":1783000156,"nonce":"SCmbExoUqMiXyXnxWZoODSTU160=","title":"Custom tiers — design spec (approved 2026-07-02)"},{"type":2,"timestamp":1783000156,"nonce":"MmH61HhnBstxTEAAi7u9b72Oar0=","status":"accepted"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783023112,"nonce":"EHt7VJhr21bbkyVfDolv5KFKl44=","body":"# Custom tiers — design spec (approved 2026-07-02)\n\nDecisions taken with Trevor 2026-07-02: config files are **YAML only**;\nfavorites/aliases **travel with the tier** (entry DAG, team-shared). Review\nanswers folded in 2026-07-02 (see \"Resolved questions\"); the spec is now\napproved for implementation.\n\n## Goal\n\nAny number of user-defined tiers, each typed `personal` or `shared`, each with\nits own remote. The three built-ins stay; `private` remains singular,\nunpushable, and non-replicable (no custom tier may be typed `private` — the\n\"structurally cannot leave\" guarantee stays unique and auditable).\n\n## Model\n\n- A tier is `{name, type: personal|shared}`. Name rules: `[a-z][a-z0-9-]{1,31}`,\n  reserved: `private`, `personal`, `shared`, `pushed`, `incoming`.\n- Ref namespace: `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` (unchanged scheme; names cannot collide\n  with the built-ins by the reserved list).\n- **Definition lives in git config** (machine-local, like remotes today):\n  `kref.tier.\u003cname\u003e = personal|shared`. The remote stays\n  `kref.remote.\u003cname\u003e = \u003cremote\u003e`. Rationale: remotes are already per-machine;\n  a tier definition without its remote is inert, so they belong together.\n- **Discovery over declaration for reads**: list/show/sync-pull resolve tiers\n  from config ∪ existing `refs/kref-*` namespaces, so entries pulled from a\n  teammate who has extra tiers still render (typed as `shared` for display,\n  flagged `(undeclared)`) instead of being invisible. Writes (`new --tier`,\n  `retier`) require the tier to be declared.\n\n## Semantics by surface\n\n- `kref tier add \u003cname\u003e --type personal|shared [--remote \u003cname\u003e [url]]` —\n  declaring and wiring the remote in one step (remote flags optional).\n  `kref tier rm \u003cname\u003e` (refuses while `refs/kref-\u003cname\u003e/*` is non-empty;\n  `--force` to orphan) / `kref tier list`.\n- **Ordering/display**: private first, then personal-typed (built-in first,\n  then customs alphabetically), then shared-typed. Glyphs AND colors are\n  type-based: `●` red for private, `◐` yellow for personal-typed, `○` green\n  for shared-typed — matching today's palette. The TIER column shows the\n  name, so customs are distinguishable by name, colored by type. No per-tier\n  color configuration.\n- **One movement verb**: `kref promote` and `kref private` are REMOVED\n  (pre-release, no compat shim). `kref retier \u003cid\u003e \u003cname\u003e` is the single way\n  to move an entry; it works for any declared tier, and the secret rescan\n  fires when the destination type is shared (same fail-closed path as today).\n  This also dissolves the \"which shared tier does promote target?\" ambiguity —\n  the user always names the destination.\n- **sync**: push/pull iterate all declared tiers with remotes; per-tier\n  pushed-state bookkeeping keys by tier name (`refs/kref-pushed/\u003cname\u003e/...`)\n  — already name-scoped today.\n- **bundle/vault**: `--tier` accepts custom names; vault stays private-only.\n- **completion**: tier enums become dynamic (store-backed), like `--kind`.\n\n## Migration/compat\n\nNone needed pre-release. Ref scheme unchanged for built-ins. Removing\n`promote`/`private` touches: commands, completion, help preamble, README,\ndemo tapes (if they use promote), and the retier quarantine hint text\n(`kref retier \u003cid\u003e shared` already the canonical phrasing).\n\n## Resolved questions (Trevor, 2026-07-02)\n\n1. Display color for custom tiers → **inherit the type color** (private=red,\n   personal=yellow, shared=green). No per-tier color config.\n2. `kref tier add --remote` in one step → **yes** (optional flags).\n3. `promote` multi-shared-tier targeting → **moot**: `promote` and `private`\n   are removed entirely; `retier` is sufficient and always explicit.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- No per-tier encryption, ACLs, or server-side enforcement (unchanged trust\n  model: a remote you can push to is a remote anyone with access can read).\n- Favorites/aliases are a separate spec (synced via entry DAG per decision).\n\n\n## Implementation amendment (Claude, 2026-07-02 — as built)\n\nBuilt and merged to main 2026-07-02; `task check` green. Two judgment calls\nwhere the spec's surface syntax could not be implemented literally:\n\n1. `kref tier add \u003cname\u003e --type ... [--remote \u003cname\u003e [url]]` — a single flag\n   cannot carry two values, so the one-step remote wiring is\n   `--remote \u003cname\u003e --url \u003curl\u003e` (`--url` requires `--remote`; both optional).\n2. \"flagged (undeclared)\" — surfaces in `kref tier list`'s REMOTE column\n   (with the `kref tier add` hint), not per-row in `kref list`; entries in\n   discovered tiers render normally (shared-typed badge with the tier's own\n   name).\n\nAdditions the spec implied but did not spell out: `Snapshot.TierType` (new\n`tier_type` field in --json output) carries the resolved type to the renderer;\ncustom-namespace lamport clocks are witnessed post-open (mirroring\nOpenGoGitRepo's built-in loader pass); `tier rm` on a populated tier refuses\nwithout `--force`, and `--force` orphans (namespace becomes\ndiscovered/read-only — refs are never deleted).\n"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1783133416,"nonce":"AILehbliD4Tpxalr5sK9rFLcJ8c=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_